"{\"uid\": \"standard.co.uk-sport-sport-olympics-why-runners-wear-arm-sleeves-paris-olympics-b1174820.html\", \"text\": \"To use the search feature, we need your consent to load Google Custom Search, which may use cookies or similar technologies. Please click 'Allow and Continue' below to enable search. See our privacy policy for more information.  Sport|Olympics  Over the weekend, the track and field events began at the Paris 2024 Olympics.  Among the most popular events of the Games, theathleticsactionhas included a dramatic men's 100m final whenNoah Lyles came from behind to pip Kishane Thompsonby five thousandths of a second and take gold for USA.  The women's 100m final was equally as exciting. Julien Alfred, the 23-year-old St Lucian,powered away from Sha'Carri Richardson to claim gold- and win the first ever Olympic medal for the Caribbean nation.  Viewers of the weekend's events might have spotted that some of the athletes competing inrunningwere wearing arm sleeves.  While they undoubtedly add a splash of style to any running outfit, arm sleeves offer much more than just aesthetic appeal. These accessories have gained popularity among athletes for a range of practical benefits, from performance enhancement to recovery support. Here's everything you need to know.  One of the main reasons some runners opt for arm sleeves is to protect their skin from the sun's harmful ultraviolet (UV) rays. While sunscreen can be effective, it often needs reapplication during longer distance runs, and can be uncomfortable when mixed with sweat.  Arm sleeves made with UV-resistant materials provide consistent protection without the need for reapplication, allowing runners to focus on their performance rather than worrying about sunburn or long-term skin damage.  For Olympians, compression technology is probably the main reason for the popularity of arm sleeves. The snug fit of compression sleeves applies gentle pressure to the muscles in the arms, which can enhance circulation and increase oxygen delivery to the muscles.  This improved blood flow can lead to better performance and reduced muscle fatigue. Compression can also aid in recovery by decreasing the buildup of lactic acid and minimising muscle soreness after a run.  Arm sleeves can also play an important role in temperature regulation, making them suitable for both hot and cold conditions. In cooler weather, the sleeves act as an additional layer that helps retain body heat, keeping muscles warm and reducing the risk of injury.  NBA London 2026 LIVE: Memphis Grizzlies vs Orlando Magic come to the UK  Aquatics GB 'immensely disappointed' as Proud joins Enhanced Games  Sports quiz of 2024: 100 hard questions on an incredible year  Winter escapes and activities to end the year in style  Conversely, in warmer climates, specially designed sleeves made from moisture-wicking fabrics can help keep runners cool by drawing sweat away from the skin and allowing it to evaporate more efficiently.  MORE ABOUT  Have your say...  1  Crime  Fight breaks out on Elizabeth line train after youths told to stop vaping by middle-aged passenger  Fight breaks out on Elizabeth line after youths told to stop vaping  2  Football  Liverpool XI vs Brighton: Starting lineup, confirmed team news, injury latest for Premier League today  Liverpool XI vs Brighton: Starting lineup and confirmed team news  3  UK  Flights alert: UK issues global travel disruption warning over Donald Trump's Iran war  Flights alert: UK issues global travel disruption warning on Iran war  4  Lifestyle  Horoscope today: Your daily guide for Saturday, March 21, 2026  Horoscope today: Your daily guide for Saturday, March 21, 2026  5  Football  Arsenal XI vs Man City: Confirmed team news, predicted lineup, injury latest for Carabao Cup final  Arsenal XI vs Man City: Confirmed team news and predicted lineup\"}"